04260nam a22006495i 9780889205833DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061995xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892058337 a10.51644/97808892058332doi  a(DE-B1597)667579  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aSOC0280002bisacsh1 aTomm, Winnie, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBodied Mindfulness :bWomen’s Spirits, Bodies and Places /cWinnie Tomm. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (356 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tSelf as Spiritual -- tSpirituality and the Body -- tSexuality and Language -- tEthics of Connectedness and Resistance -- tExclusionary Politics at Work -- tTowards 'Living With' -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  a“I see spirituality and social change to be integrally related to each other. I believe that liberation efforts that are supported by spiritual experiences of integration promote human dignity as well as social equality.” Bodied Mindfulness combines spiritual, social and analytical perspectives to explore topics central to women’s development: spirituality, women’s bodies, cultural constructions of women’s sexuality in language, sexual ethics, the sexual contract in politics and at work, and the relation between nature and culture. It is Tomm’s deeply held conviction that women need to bring a vital spirituality to feminist social criticism in order to resolve these issues and increase their power to promote social justice and ecological balance. Tomm embraces a vast store of knowledge from diverse sources, including Buddhist, shamanist and feminist resources. In a move away from abstract theorizing, she explicitly connects theory with realities lived by women. Grounding theory in personal experience — her own and others — Tomm delivers a powerful and empowering account of women’s spirituality. The resulting ontological transformation allows women to live deeply in the body while strengthening their relation to human and non-human matter and energy. Bodied Mindfulness will be of great interest to feminist scholars in all disciplines, but most particularly to those in Women’s Studies and Religious Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCulture. 0aEsprit et corps. 0aFeminismxReligious aspects. 0aFeminist spirituality. 0aFeminist theory. 0aFemmesxIdentité. 0aFemmesxMorale sexuelle. 0aFéminismexAspect moral. 0aNature. 0aSpiritualité féministe. 0aThéorie féministe. 4aPhilosophy. 4aReligion. 4aReligion: Spirituality. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920583340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889205833423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889205833/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles